AST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh: traditional spelling of   Griffith  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Welsh (Carmarthenshire and western England): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Gruffudd</i>, Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, composed of the elements <i>grip</i>, of uncertain significance, + <i>iud</i> ‘chief, lord’."]}]},{"name":"Gruffudd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffudd","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Gruffud","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Gruffudd ."]}]},{"name":"\"Fychan\"","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Welsh: A Welsh name of great antiquity, from vyckan, little, small; i.e. small in stature. Compare the surname Bychan and the Armoric Le Bihan."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gruffudd \"Fychan\" ap Gruffudd was born about 1182, in Denbigh, Denbighshire, Wales. He married Gwladus ferch Gruffudd. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died about 1280, in his hometown, at the age of 100, and was buried in Denbigh, Denbighshire, Wales."},"et":{"about 1182–about 1280":"umbes 1182–umbes 1280","1184–1280":"1184–1280","1208–1300":"1208–1300","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1182–1280":"1182–1280","about 1208":"umbes 1208","about 1280":"umbes 1280","about 1182":"umbes 1182","1300":"1300","1210":"1210","1184":"1184","about 1210":"umbes 1210","1182":"1182","1208":"1208","1280":"1280","Denbigh, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbigh, Denbighshire, Wales","Ystrad-dyfodwg, Glamorgan, Wales":"Ystrad, Glamorgan, Wales","Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1182–about 1280":"noin 1182–noin 1280","1184–1280":"1184–1280","1208–1300":"1208–1300","1210–Male":"1210–Kuollut","1182–1280":"1182–1280","about 1208":"noin 1208","about 1280":"noin 1280","about 1182":"noin 1182","1300":"1300","1210":"1210","1184":"1184","about 1210":"noin 1210","1182":"1182","1208":"1208","1280":"1280","Denbigh, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbigh, Denbighshire, Wales","Ystrad-dyfodwg, Glamorgan, Wales":"Ystrad, Glamorgan, Wales","Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1182–about 1280":"environ 1182–environ 1280","1184–1280":"1184–1280","1208–1300":"1208–1300","1210–Male":"1210–Décédé","1182–1280":"1182–1280","about 1208":"environ 1208","about 1280":"environ 1280","about 1182":"environ 1182","1300":"1300","1210":"1210","1184":"1184","about 1210":"environ 1210","1182":"1182","1208":"1208","1280":"1280","Denbigh, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbigh, Denbighshire, Galles","Ystrad-dyfodwg, Glamorgan, Wales":"Ystrad, Glamorgan, Galles","Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Gruffudd \"Fychan\" ap Gruffudd est né environ 1182, à Denbigh, Denbighshire, Galles. Il a épousé Gwladus ferch Gruffudd. Ils ont eu au moins 2 fils. Il est décédé environ 1280, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 100 ans, et a été enterré à Denbigh, Denbigh